{"timestamp": "2026-05-26 17:39:10,947", "level": "INFO", "logger": "flow.execution", "module": "flow", "function": "run_async", "line": 205, "message": " - task0: ```python\nimport re\n\ndef analyze_job_description(job_description: str):\n    \"\"\"Analyzes the job description text and extracts required skills, responsibilities, and criteria sections.\n    Returns a dictionary with three keys: 'skills', 'responsibilities', and 'criteria', each containing a list of strings.\n    \"\"\"\n    # Define section headings and regex patterns\n    section_patterns = {\n        'skills': r'(?:required skills|skills required|skills|technical skills):?\\\\s*(.*?)(?=\\\\n{2,}|\\Z)',\n        'responsibilities': r'(?:responsibilities|key responsibilities|job duties):?\\\\s*(.*?)(?=\\\\n{2,}|\\Z)',\n        'criteria': r'(?:requirements|qualifications|criteria|experience needed):?\\\\s*(.*?)(?=\\\\n{2,}|\\Z)'\n    }\n    results = {'skills': [], 'responsibilities': [], 'criteria': []}\n\n    # Normalize whitespace\n    text = job_description + '\\\\n\\\\n'\n\n    for section, pattern in section_patterns.items():\n        match = re.search(pattern, text, re.IGNORECASE | re.DOTALL)\n        if match:\n            block = match.group(1).strip()\n            # Split by lines or common delimiters\n            lines = re.split(r'[\\\\n•\\\\-]+', block)\n            for item in lines:\n                item = item.strip(' :;,.').replace(\"*\", \"\")\n                if item:\n                    results[section].append(item)\n\n    # Fallback keyword-based extraction if sections are sparse or not found, focusing on skills\n    if not results['skills']:\n        keywords = ['Python', 'Java', 'communication', 'SQL', 'AWS', 'JavaScript', 'C++', 'C#', 'React', 'Angular', 'Node.js', 'Data Analysis', 'Machine Learning', 'Deep Learning', 'Cloud Computing', 'Project Management', 'Testing', 'DevOps'] # Expanded keyword list\n        for kw in keywords:\n            if re.search(r'\\\\b' + re.escape(kw) + r'\\\\b', text, re.IGNORECASE):\n                results['skills'].append(kw)\n\n    return results['skills'], results['responsibilities'], results['criteria']\n```"}
{"timestamp": "2026-05-26 17:39:10,947", "level": "INFO", "logger": "flow.execution", "module": "flow", "function": "run_async", "line": 205, "message": " - task1: ```python\n[\n    \"Parse job description text to extract and structure requirements (skills, years, responsibilities).\",\n    \"Normalize extracted job requirements (standardize terminology, handle synonyms and variants).\",\n    \"Parse resume content (TXT, PDF) to plain text.\",\n    \"Extract key resume elements: skills, experiences (with dates), education, and project descriptions.\",\n    \"Normalize resume skills using the same taxonomy as job requirements.\",\n    \"Perform exact match mapping between resume skills and job requirements.\",\n    \"Perform semantic similarity matching (e.g., using word embeddings or pretrained language models) to catch related skills.\",\n    \"For each requirement, collect all matching resume entries and quantify proficiency (years, project count, role level).\",\n    \"Assign weights to job requirements based on importance from the job description.\",\n    \"Calculate a per-requirement match score: weighted combination of exact and semantic match strengths.\",\n    \"Aggregate per-requirement scores into an overall resume–job match score.\",\n    \"Generate a detailed mapping report showing each job requirement, matched resume evidence, and individual scores.\",\n    \"Highlight strengths (high-scoring requirements) and gaps (unmatched or low scores).\",\n    \"Provide a JSON-serializable output with structured fields: requirements, matches, scores, overall_score.\",\n    \"Log and store parsed data and final results for downstream processing.\"\n]\n```\n"}
{"timestamp": "2026-05-26 17:39:10,947", "level": "INFO", "logger": "flow.execution", "module": "flow", "function": "run_async", "line": 205, "message": " - task2: ```python\nimport smtplib\nfrom email.message import EmailMessage\nfrom typing import List, Dict\n\nclass EmailSender:\n    def __init__(self, smtp_server: str, smtp_port: int, username: str, password: str, use_tls: bool = True):\n        \"\"\"\n        Initialize the email sender with SMTP server details.\n        \"\"\"\n        self.smtp_server = smtp_server\n        self.smtp_port = smtp_port\n        self.username = username\n        self.password = password\n        self.use_tls = use_tls\n\n    def send_email(self, recipient: str, subject: str, body: str) -> bool:\n        \"\"\"\n        Sends a single email. Returns True if successful, False otherwise.\n        \"\"\"\n        try:\n            msg = EmailMessage()\n            msg[\"From\"] = self.username\n            msg[\"To\"] = recipient\n            msg[\"Subject\"] = subject\n            msg.set_content(body)\n\n            with smtplib.SMTP(self.smtp_server, self.smtp_port) as server:\n                if self.use_tls:\n                    server.starttls()\n                server.login(self.username, self.password)\n                server.send_message(msg)\n            print(f\"Email sent to {recipient} with subject '{subject}'\")\n            return True\n        except Exception as e:\n            print(f\"Failed to send email to {recipient}: {e}\")\n            return False\n\n    def send_notification(self, recipients: List[str], notification_subject: str, notification_body: str) -> Dict[str, bool]:\n        \"\"\"\n        Send a generic notification email to multiple recipients.\n        Returns a dict mapping each recipient to True/False based on success.\n        \"\"\"\n        results = {}\n        for email in recipients:\n            success = self.send_email(email, notification_subject, notification_body)\n            results[email] = success\n        return results\n\n    def send_interview_invite(self, candidate_email: str, candidate_name: str, interview_date: str, instructions: str) -> bool:\n        \"\"\"\n        Send an interview invitation to a single candidate.\n        \"\"\"\n        subject = f\"Interview Invitation for {candidate_name}\"\n        body = (\n            f\"Hello {candidate_name},\\n\\n\"\n            f\"You are invited to an interview on {interview_date}.\\n\"\n            f\"Instructions:\\n{instructions}\\n\\n\"\n            \"Please reply to confirm your availability.\\n\\n\"\n            \"Best regards,\\n\"\n            \"Recruitment Team\"\n        )\n        return self.send_email(candidate_email, subject, body)\n\n# Example usage\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    smtp_config = {\n        \"smtp_server\": \"smtp.example.com\",\n        \"smtp_port\": 587,\n        \"username\": \"recruiter@example.com\",\n        \"password\": \"securepassword\",\n        \"use_tls\": True\n    }\n\n    email_sender = EmailSender(**smtp_config)\n\n    # Send a generic notification\n    notifications = email_sender.send_notification(\n        recipients=[\"applicant1@example.com\", \"applicant2@example.com\"],\n        notification_subject=\"Application Received\",\n        notification_body=\"Thank you for applying. We have received your application and will be in touch.\"\n    )\n    print(\"Notification results:\", notifications)\n\n    # Send an interview invite\n    invite_success = email_sender.send_interview_invite(\n        candidate_email=\"candidate@example.com\",\n        candidate_name=\"Jane Doe\",\n        interview_date=\"2024-07-01 10:00 AM\",\n        instructions=\"Please join the Zoom meeting with the link provided in the calendar invite.\"\n    )\n    print(\"Interview invite sent:\", invite_success)\n```\n"}
{"timestamp": "2026-05-26 17:39:10,948", "level": "INFO", "logger": "flow.execution", "module": "flow", "function": "run_async", "line": 205, "message": " - task3: ```python\nclass TechnicalInterviewConductor:\n    def __init__(self, questions):\n        \"\"\"\n        Initializes the interview conductor with a list of questions.\n        \"\"\"\n        self.questions = questions\n        self.responses = {}\n\n    def present_question(self, question_number):\n        \"\"\"\n        Presents a question to the candidate and captures the response.\n        \"\"\"\n        if 1 <= question_number <= len(self.questions):\n            question = self.questions[question_number - 1]\n            print(f\"Question {question_number}: {question}\")\n            response = input(\"Your answer: \")  # Capture response via console input\n            self.responses[question] = response\n            return True\n        else:\n            print(\"Invalid question number.\")\n            return False\n\n    def get_response(self, question):\n        \"\"\"\n        Returns the candidate's response to a specific question.\n        \"\"\"\n        return self.responses.get(question, None)\n\n    def conduct_interview(self):\n        \"\"\"\n        Conducts the entire interview, presenting each question sequentially.\n        \"\"\"\n        for i in range(1, len(self.questions) + 1):\n            self.present_question(i)\n\n    def get_all_responses(self):\n        \"\"\"\n        Returns all captured responses as a dictionary.\n        \"\"\"\n        return self.responses\n\n# Example Usage\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    sample_questions = [\n        \"Explain the concept of polymorphism in object-oriented programming.\",\n        \"Describe the difference between a stack and a queue.\",\n        \"What are the advantages of using a relational database?\",\n        \"How does garbage collection work in Python?\",\n        \"Explain the concept of recursion and provide an example.\"\n    ]\n\n    interviewer = TechnicalInterviewConductor(sample_questions)\n    interviewer.conduct_interview()\n\n    all_responses = interviewer.get_all_responses()\n    print(\"\\nAll Responses:\")\n    for question, answer in all_responses.items():\n        print(f\"Question: {question}\\nAnswer: {answer}\\n\")\n```"}
{"timestamp": "2026-05-26 17:39:10,948", "level": "INFO", "logger": "flow.execution", "module": "flow", "function": "run_async", "line": 205, "message": " - task4: ```python\nimport re\n\nclass ScoringModule:\n    def __init__(self, criteria_weights, question_rubric):\n        \"\"\"\n        Initializes the scoring module.\n        - criteria_weights: dict of {criterion_name: weight_float}\n        - question_rubric: dict of {\n              question_text: {\n                  \"expected_keywords\": [str, ...],\n                  \"min_length\": int\n              },\n              ...\n          }\n        \"\"\"\n        self.weights = criteria_weights\n        self.rubric = question_rubric\n\n    def _score_completeness(self, response, min_length):\n        \"\"\"Score completeness based on meeting a minimum length.\"\"\"\n        length = len(response.split())\n        return min(length / min_length, 1.0) if min_length > 0 else 1.0\n\n    def _score_correctness(self, response, expected_keywords):\n        \"\"\"Score correctness by keyword coverage.\"\"\"\n        response_lower = response.lower()\n        found = sum(1 for kw in expected_keywords if kw.lower() in response_lower)\n        total = len(expected_keywords)\n        return (found / total) if total > 0 else 1.0\n\n    def _score_clarity(self, response):\n        \"\"\"\n        Score clarity based on average sentence length.\n        Shorter sentences often read more clearly.\n        \"\"\"\n        sentences = re.split(r'[.!?]+', response)\n        words = response.split()\n        if not sentences or not words:\n            return 0.0\n        avg_words_per_sentence = len(words) / max(len(sentences), 1)\n        # Ideal average ~15 words/sentence; normalize so that <=15 -> score=1, >=30 -> 0\n        score = max(0.0, min((30 - avg_words_per_sentence) / 15, 1.0))\n        return score\n\n    def score_response(self, question, response):\n        \"\"\"\n        Returns a dict of raw criterion scores and the weighted total.\n        \"\"\"\n        rubric = self.rubric.get(question, {})\n        completeness_raw = self._score_completeness(\n            response,\n            rubric.get(\"min_length\", 50)\n        )\n        correctness_raw = self._score_correctness(\n            response,\n            rubric.get(\"expected_keywords\", [])\n        )\n        clarity_raw = self._score_clarity(response)\n\n        # Weighted sum\n        total_score = (\n            completeness_raw * self.weights.get(\"Completeness\", 0) +\n            correctness_raw * self.weights.get(\"Correctness\", 0) +\n            clarity_raw * self.weights.get(\"Clarity\", 0)\n        )\n\n        return {\n            \"Completeness\": completeness_raw,\n            \"Correctness\": correctness_raw,\n            \"Clarity\": clarity_raw,\n            \"Total\": total_score\n        }\n\n    def calculate_total_score(self, responses):\n        \"\"\"\n        responses: dict of {question_text: response_text}\n        Returns a dict of {question: score_dict}, plus overall total.\n        \"\"\"\n        detailed = {}\n        overall = 0.0\n        for q, resp in responses.items():\n            scores = self.score_response(q, resp)\n            detailed[q] = scores\n            overall += scores[\"Total\"]\n        detailed[\"Overall_Total\"] = overall\n        return detailed\n\n    def generate_feedback(self, question, score_dict):\n        \"\"\"\n        Provides criterion-specific feedback.\n        \"\"\"\n        feedback = []\n        for crit in (\"Completeness\", \"Correctness\", \"Clarity\"):\n            raw = score_dict[crit]\n            if raw >= 0.8:\n                feedback.append(f\"{crit}: Good.\")\n            elif raw >= 0.5:\n                feedback.append(f\"{crit}: Acceptable, could improve.\")\n            else:\n                feedback.append(f\"{crit}: Needs improvement.\")\n        return f\"Feedback for '{question}': \" + \" \".join(feedback)\n\n\n# Example Usage\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    weights = {\n        \"Completeness\": 0.3,\n        \"Correctness\":   0.5,\n        \"Clarity\":       0.2\n    }\n\n    rubric = {\n        \"Explain the concept of polymorphism in object-oriented programming.\": {\n            \"expected_keywords\": [\"object\", \"method\", \"inheritance\", \"override\"],\n            \"min_length\": 20\n        },\n        \"Describe the difference between a stack and a queue.\": {\n            \"expected_keywords\": [\"lifo\", \"fifo\", \"push\", \"pop\", \"enqueue\", \"dequeue\"],\n            \"min_length\": 15\n        },\n         \"What are the advantages of using a relational database?\": {\n            \"expected_keywords\": [\"data integrity\", \"structured data\", \"SQL\", \"relationships\"],\n            \"min_length\": 15\n        },\n        \"How does garbage collection work in Python?\": {\n            \"expected_keywords\": [\"reference counting\", \"cyclic garbage collection\", \"memory management\"],\n            \"min_length\": 15\n        },\n        \"Explain the concept of recursion and provide an example.\": {\n            \"expected_keywords\": [\"base case\", \"recursive call\", \"function calls itself\"],\n            \"min_length\": 20\n        }\n    }\n\n    scorer = ScoringModule(weights, rubric)\n\n    sample_responses = {\n        \"Explain the concept of polymorphism in object-oriented programming.\":\n            \"Polymorphism allows objects of different classes to be treated as instances of the same class through inheritance and method overriding.\",\n        \"Describe the difference between a stack and a queue.\":\n            \"A stack is LIFO: push and pop happen at the same end. A queue is FIFO: enqueue at one end and dequeue at the other.\",\n        \"What are the advantages of using a relational database?\":\n            \"They are structured and use SQL.\",\n        \"How does garbage collection work in Python?\":\n            \"It automatically frees up memory using reference counting.\",\n        \"Explain the concept of recursion and provide an example.\":\n            \"Recursion is when a function calls itself until it hits a base case.\"\n    }\n\n    results = scorer.calculate_total_score(sample_responses)\n    for question, scores in results.items():\n        if question == \"Overall_Total\":\n            print(f\"Overall Total Score: {scores:.2f}\")\n        else:\n            print(f\"\\nQuestion: {question}\")\n            print(f\"Scores: {scores}\")\n            print(scorer.generate_feedback(question, scores))\n```"}
{"timestamp": "2026-05-26 17:39:10,948", "level": "INFO", "logger": "flow.execution", "module": "flow", "function": "run_async", "line": 205, "message": " - task5: ```python\nfrom typing import List, Dict\n\nclass EvaluationReportGenerator:\n    def __init__(\n        self,\n        email_sender,\n        scoring_module,\n        job_analyzer,\n        resume_analyzer,\n        job_description: str,\n        resume: str\n    ):\n        self.email_sender = email_sender\n        self.scoring_module = scoring_module\n        self.job_analyzer = job_analyzer\n        self.resume_analyzer = resume_analyzer\n        self.job_description = job_description\n        self.resume = resume\n\n    def generate_report(\n        self,\n        candidate_name: str,\n        candidate_email: str,\n        interview_responses: Dict[str, str]\n    ) -> List[str]:\n        \"\"\"\n        Generates a final evaluation report as a list of strings,\n        including job analysis, resume analysis, interview scores, and feedback.\n        \"\"\"\n        # 1. Analyze job description\n        job_analysis: List[str] = self.job_analyzer.analyze(self.job_description)\n\n        # 2. Analyze candidate resume\n        resume_analysis: List[str] = self.resume_analyzer.analyze(self.resume)\n\n        # 3. Score the candidate responses\n        scores: Dict[str, Dict[str, float]] = self.scoring_module.calculate_total_score(interview_responses)\n\n        # 4. Generate feedback for each question (excluding overall total)\n        feedback: Dict[str, str] = {}\n        for question, score_dict in scores.items():\n            if question != \"Overall_Total\":\n                feedback[question] = self.scoring_module.generate_feedback(question, score_dict)\n\n        # 5. Build the report as a list of strings\n        report_lines: List[str] = []\n        report_lines.append(f\"Candidate Name: {candidate_name}\")\n        report_lines.append(f\"Candidate Email: {candidate_email}\")\n        report_lines.append(\"----- Job Analysis -----\")\n        report_lines.extend(job_analysis)\n        report_lines.append(\"----- Resume Analysis -----\")\n        report_lines.extend(resume_analysis)\n        report_lines.append(\"----- Interview Scores -----\")\n        for question, score_dict in scores.items():\n            report_lines.append(f\"{question}: {score_dict}\")\n        report_lines.append(\"----- Feedback -----\")\n        for question, fb in feedback.items():\n            report_lines.append(f\"{question}: {fb}\")\n\n        return report_lines\n\n    def send_report(self, candidate_email: str, report_lines: List[str]) -> None:\n        \"\"\"\n        Sends the evaluation report via email.\n        \"\"\"\n        subject = f\"Final Evaluation Report for {report_lines[0].split(': ', 1)[1]}\"\n        body = \"\\n\".join(report_lines)\n        self.email_sender.send_email(candidate_email, subject, body)\n        print(f\"Evaluation report sent to {candidate_email}\")\n\n\n# Example Usage\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    # Dummy implementations for demonstration\n    class DummyEmailSender:\n        def send_email(self, recipient: str, subject: str, body: str) -> bool:\n            print(f\"Email sent to: {recipient}\\nSubject: {subject}\\nBody:\\n{body}\")\n            return True\n\n    class DummyJobAnalyzer:\n        def analyze(self, job_description: str) -> List[str]:\n            return [\n                \"Key Responsibilities: Develop backend services, manage databases.\",\n                \"Required Skills: Python, REST APIs, SQL.\"\n            ]\n\n    class DummyResumeAnalyzer:\n        def analyze(self, resume: str) -> List[str]:\n            return [\n                \"Strengths: 5 years Python experience, strong DB design.\",\n                \"Areas to Improve: Exposure to microservices could be deeper.\"\n            ]\n\n    class DummyScoringModule:\n        def __init__(self):\n            self.weights = {\n                \"Completeness\": 0.3,\n                \"Correctness\":   0.5,\n                \"Clarity\":       0.2\n            }\n            self.rubric = {\n                \"Explain the concept of polymorphism in object-oriented programming.\": {\n                    \"expected_keywords\": [\"object\", \"method\", \"inheritance\", \"override\"],\n                    \"min_length\": 20\n                },\n                \"Describe the difference between a stack and a queue.\": {\n                    \"expected_keywords\": [\"lifo\", \"fifo\", \"push\", \"pop\", \"enqueue\", \"dequeue\"],\n                    \"min_length\": 15\n                },\n                \"What are the advantages of using a relational database?\": {\n                    \"expected_keywords\": [\"data integrity\", \"structured data\", \"SQL\", \"relationships\"],\n                    \"min_length\": 15\n                },\n                \"How does garbage collection work in Python?\": {\n                    \"expected_keywords\": [\"reference counting\", \"cyclic garbage collection\", \"memory management\"],\n                    \"min_length\": 15\n                },\n                \"Explain the concept of recursion and provide an example.\": {\n                    \"expected_keywords\": [\"base case\", \"recursive call\", \"function calls itself\"],\n                    \"min_length\": 20\n                }\n            }\n\n        def calculate_total_score(self, responses: Dict[str, str]) -> Dict[str, Dict[str, float]]:\n            detailed = {}\n            overall = 0.0\n            for q, resp in responses.items():\n                scores = self.score_response(q, resp)\n                detailed[q] = scores\n                overall += scores[\"Total\"]\n            detailed[\"Overall_Total\"] = overall\n            return detailed\n\n        def generate_feedback(self, question: str, score_dict: Dict[str, float]) -> str:\n            feedback_parts = []\n            for crit in (\"Completeness\", \"Correctness\", \"Clarity\"):\n                raw = score_dict[crit]\n                if raw >= 0.8:\n                    feedback_parts.append(f\"{crit}: Good.\")\n                elif raw >= 0.5:\n                    feedback_parts.append(f\"{crit}: Acceptable, could improve.\")\n                else:\n                    feedback_parts.append(f\"{crit}: Needs improvement.\")\n            return f\"Feedback for '{question}': \" + \" \".join(feedback_parts)\n\n        def _score_completeness(self, response: str, min_length: int) -> float:\n            length = len(response.split())\n            return min(length / min_length, 1.0) if min_length > 0 else 1.0\n\n        def _score_correctness(self, response: str, expected_keywords: List[str]) -> float:\n            response_lower = response.lower()\n            found = sum(1 for kw in expected_keywords if kw.lower() in response_lower)\n            total = len(expected_keywords)\n            return (found / total) if total > 0 else 1.0\n\n        def _score_clarity(self, response: str) -> float:\n            import re\n            sentences = re.split(r'[.!?]+', response)\n            words = response.split()\n            if not sentences or not words:\n                return 0.0\n            avg_words = len(words) / max(len(sentences), 1)\n            score = max(0.0, min((30 - avg_words) / 15, 1.0))\n            return score\n\n        def score_response(self, question: str, response: str) -> Dict[str, float]:\n            rubric = self.rubric.get(question, {})\n            completeness = self._score_completeness(response, rubric.get(\"min_length\", 50))\n            correctness = self._score_correctness(response, rubric.get(\"expected_keywords\", []))\n            clarity = self._score_clarity(response)\n            total = (\n                completeness * self.weights[\"Completeness\"] +\n                correctness * self.weights[\"Correctness\"] +\n                clarity * self.weights[\"Clarity\"]\n            )\n            return {\n                \"Completeness\": completeness,\n                \"Correctness\": correctness,\n                \"Clarity\": clarity,\n                \"Total\": total\n            }\n\n    # Instantiate and run\n    email_sender = DummyEmailSender()\n    scoring_module = DummyScoringModule()\n    job_analyzer = DummyJobAnalyzer()\n    resume_analyzer = DummyResumeAnalyzer()\n\n    job_description = \"Software Engineer role: build APIs, maintain databases.\"\n    resume = \"John has 5 years in Python and SQL, led two major projects.\"\n\n    report_generator = EvaluationReportGenerator(\n        email_sender,\n        scoring_module,\n        job_analyzer,\n        resume_analyzer,\n        job_description,\n        resume\n    )\n\n    candidate_name = \"John Doe\"\n    candidate_email = \"john.doe@example.com\"\n    interview_responses = {\n        \"Explain the concept of polymorphism in object-oriented programming.\": (\n            \"Polymorphism allows objects of different classes to be treated as \"\n            \"instances of the same class through inheritance and method overriding.\"\n        ),\n        \"Describe the difference between a stack and a queue.\": (\n            \"A stack is LIFO: push and pop happen at the same end. \"\n            \"A queue is FIFO: enqueue at one end and dequeue at the other.\"\n        ),\n        \"What are the advantages of using a relational database?\": \"They are structured and use SQL.\",\n        \"How does garbage collection work in Python?\": \"It automatically frees up memory using reference counting.\",\n        \"Explain the concept of recursion and provide an example.\": (\n            \"Recursion is when a function calls itself until it hits a base case.\"\n        )\n    }\n\n    report_lines = report_generator.generate_report(\n        candidate_name, candidate_email, interview_responses\n    )\n    print(\"Report Lines:\", report_lines)\n\n    report_generator.send_report(candidate_email, report_lines)\n```"}
